content.description:
Climb follows up through a dike. Great movement up through the middle.  

  That green line on the beta photo may or may not be accurate. go find out. 

  It's a good line.
content.protection: Eight bolts and maybe some small gear for the flake (?)
content.location:
On the west face of Java, located opposite of Coral Reef. 

  See beta photo, it's roughly accurate.

content.description: "Led A-Stray" follows the crack system between "Shady Proposition" and "Climbus Interuptus". Once the crack ends there are still some small rp placements and then it moves slightly left and straight up the face past one bolt to the top and left to the anchors above "Shady Proposition". The climbing through the crux section is tweaky on the elbows and or shoulders but has decent gear. The climbing above the tiny rp's is a bit too hard for the available protection, so I have yet to recomend this route to anybody as a lead. It's a good top-rope though and would get better with more travel.
content.protection: Standard rack up to hand-size protection with extra rp and small camming gear.The hardest climbing is adequately protected with very serious fall potential above top of seam.One bolt high above end of seam.

content.description: Start in the dike and climb it and the crack to the arete. Then take the arete to the top, favoring the right side.
content.protection: Trad with some bolts. The anchor in the Busse/Burr guidebook does not exist. You must climb the fin over to the anchor above Shady Proposition (which has a sketchy half exposed bolt).
content.location: Java Rock, south side. To climber's right of Shady Proposition
